{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048136,"nonce":"2v6KenRnWN4WYD/fYC37dzMfJ34=","title":"Generalized loss terms from trial specifications","message":"[Imported from GitHub #10] (created 2024-02-17T01:10:45Z)\n\nCurrently:\n\n- the `init` field of [`AbstractTaskTrialSpec`](https://github.com/mlprt/feedbax/blob/308ec2055e7c03173a4bc48f12a53b87c12e54a7/feedbax/task.py#L150) specifies 1) lambdas that pick out subtrees of the model state, and 2) replacements for those subtrees, to use to initialize the state on a given trial.\n- for each batch of training trials, [`TaskTrainer`](https://github.com/mlprt/feedbax/blob/308ec2055e7c03173a4bc48f12a53b87c12e54a7/feedbax/train.py#L530) [passes](https://github.com/mlprt/feedbax/blob/308ec2055e7c03173a4bc48f12a53b87c12e54a7/feedbax/train.py#L680) the following to the loss function: 1) the evaluated trajectories of model states, 2) the trial specifications. Thus, every `AbstractLoss` subclass in `feedbax.loss` works through hardcoded references to parts of `states` and `trial_specs`. For example, [`feedbax.loss.EffectorPositionLoss`](https://github.com/mlprt/feedbax/blob/308ec2055e7c03173a4bc48f12a53b87c12e54a7/feedbax/loss.py#L315) is a function of the difference `states.mechanics.effector.pos - trial_specs.target.pos`. \n- the `target` field of `AbstractTaskTrialSpec` is a `CartesianState` that only specifies the state of a single effector.\n\nBut what if we want to (say) include losses that penalize the position of two different effectors, given by `CartesianState` leaves at different locations in the `states` PyTree? Then `trial_specs.target` should specify two different `CartesianState` targets. Should the relationship between the leaves of `trial_specs.target` and the leaves of `states` be hardcoded into a subclass of `AbstractLoss`? This could lead to a proliferation of `AbstractLoss` classes. (However, see #24.)\n\nInstead, `trial_specs.target` could be defined similarly to `trial_specs.init`. In that case, each member of `target` would provide 1) a lambda that picks out a part of the state, and 2) a target trajectory for that state. A loss term could be automatically constructed from each entry -- something like `target.where(states) - target.value`.\n\nI think some losses should still be defined the same way they already are. But this feature might make it easier to train more complex models, since the user will only need to specify a couple of lambdas when subclassing `AbstractTask`, instead of needing to write multiple subclasses of `AbstractLoss` as well.","files":null}]}